      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's dive into the technical explanation.\n\nThe dissonance of the minor second can be attributed to its spectral characteristics. The critical band theory suggests that the human ear is most sensitive to frequencies within a specific range, typically between 200 Hz and 800 Hz. The minor second, with its frequency ratio of 9:10, falls within this range, but its spectral balance is skewed towards the lower frequencies.\n\nIn particular, the minor second has a higher energy density in the lower frequencies, which can lead to a sense of tension and instability. This is because the lower frequencies are more easily perceived by the ear, and the brain's auditory system is more sensitive to these frequencies.\n\nFrom an acoustic perspective, the minor second can be thought of as a \"spectral outlier\" - its frequency ratio is not as harmonically rich as the perfect fifth, which has a frequency ratio of 3:2. The perfect fifth, on the other hand, has a more balanced spectral distribution, with a greater emphasis on the higher frequencies.\n\nIn terms of interference patterns, the minor second can be seen as a \"beat\" between the two frequencies, with the lower frequency (C) beating against",
